I"M<p>You can use this add-on to check whether your configuration files are valid against the new version of Home Assistant before you actually update your Home Assistant installation. This add-on will help you avoid errors due to breaking changes, resulting in a smooth update.</p>
<h3>How to use this add-on</h3>
<ol>
<li>Just start the add-on.</li>
<li>Wait (On a Raspberry Pi it can take several minutes).</li>
<li>If you see the following output then you are good to go to update Home Assistant: <code>[Info] Configuration check finished - no error found! :)</code>.</li>
</ol>
<p>If you get errors, then you should look for <strong>Breaking Changes</strong> against the version you specified for this add-on and change your configuration accordingly.</p>
<h3>Add-on configuration</h3>
<pre><code class="language-json">{
  &quot;version&quot;: &quot;latest&quot;
}
</code></pre>
<div class="config-vars">
  <h3><a class="title-link" name="configuration-variables" href="#configuration-variables"></a> Configuration Variables</h3>
  <dl class=''><dt><a class='title-link' name='version' href='#version'></a> version</dt><dd><p class='desc'><span class='type'>(<span class='string'>string</span>)</span><span class='required'>(Required)</span><span class='description'><p>Version of Home Assistant that you plan to install.</p>
</span></p></dd></dl>
</div>
